- Wed 17 Jul 2019. Cross-border trader's Ebola death
[LongRoom News, Reuters report, edited]
https://af.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idAFKCN1UC133
[byline: Tom Miles]

A Congolese woman who died of Ebola this month [15 Jul 2019] vomited 4 times in a Ugandan market after crossing the border days earlier to sell fish, WHO said, fuelling fears that the virus may be spreading beyond Democratic Republic of Congo.

The current outbreak of the highly infectious disease has been all but confined to Congo, killing 1673 people there -- more than 2/3 of those who contracted it -- over the past year, and 3 in Uganda last month.

The fisherwoman travelled across the border to Mpondwe market on [11 Jul 2019], according to a Ugandan Health Ministry report published on [Wed 17 Jul 2019] by WHO. It said 19 fishmongers were listed as having had possible contact with her while another 590 could be targeted for vaccination.

The health response to the virus relies on tracking down and testing people who may have been exposed to it and vaccinating them and anybody they have had contact with. Ugandan and Congolese officials were working to find people who might have been put at risk by the dead woman, who appeared to have used an illegal border crossing, health ministry spokesman Emmanuel Ainebyona said. So far "no one has been found to be positive of the Ebola virus. The team is still monitoring the tested traders," he said.

The report said health workers had not established where the fishmonger spent nights, who transported her merchandise and who cleaned up her vomit. The Ministry and WHO said there were currently no confirmed Ebola cases in Uganda.

